{{ 'ear-impression-guide.css' | asset_url | stylesheet_tag }}

<script type="application/ld+json">
{
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "HowTo",
  "name": "How to take ear impressions for AAW custom in-ear monitors",
  "description": "AAW guide for audiologist-taken silicone ear impressions for CIEM builds, including open-mouth technique, second-bend canal depth, concha coverage, quality checks, and shipping preparation.",
  "step": [
    {
      "@type": "HowToStep",
      "name": "Use a professional audiologist",
      "text": "Have impressions taken by an audiologist or trained ear-impression professional after an otoscopic ear check."
    },
    {
      "@type": "HowToStep",
      "name": "Use an open-mouth bite block",
      "text": "Keep the jaw open and stable with a bite block while both impressions cure, so the final CIEM seal remains reliable during jaw movement."
    },
    {
      "@type": "HowToStep",
      "name": "Capture past the second bend",
      "text": "The canal portion should extend beyond the second bend, with a smooth full canal stalk and enough length for secure shell modelling."
    },
    {
      "@type": "HowToStep",
      "name": "Fill the full outer ear",
      "text": "The impression should cover the full concha, helix, crus, tragus, and anti-tragus with enough thickness around the concha edge."
    },
    {
      "@type": "HowToStep",
      "name": "Inspect the finished pair",
      "text": "Reject impressions with short canals, thin outer-ear walls, bubbles, folds, drag marks, torn tips, or missing landmarks."
    },
    {
      "@type": "HowToStep",
      "name": "Pack and send both sides",
      "text": "Label left and right, keep the otoblocks attached, protect the impressions from compression, and include your order details."
    }
  ]
}
</script>

<div class="ei-page">
  <section class="ei-hero" aria-labelledby="ei-title">
    <div class="ei-wrap ei-hero-grid">
      <div class="ei-hero-copy">
        <p class="ei-kicker">CIEM build guide</p>
        <h1 id="ei-title">Ear impressions that build a better custom monitor</h1>
        <p class="ei-dek">A custom IEM can only fit as accurately as the impression we receive. For AAW builds, we need a clean, deep, full-shell pair: both ears captured open-mouth, past the second bend, with enough concha and helix detail for a stable seal.</p>
        <div class="ei-actions">
          <a class="ei-btn" href="/pages/contact">Book in Singapore</a>
          <a class="ei-btn secondary" href="#ei-quality-check">Quality checklist</a>
        </div>
      </div>
      <figure class="ei-hero-media">
        {% render 'aaw-responsive-asset-image', file: 'ear-impression-anatomy-guide.jpg', alt: 'Annotated ear impression area guide showing helix, tragus, concha, and extended canal area', width: '904', height: '890', loading: 'eager', sizes: '100vw' %}
        <figcaption><b>Target coverage</b><span>Full outer-ear fill, concha edge thickness, and canal extension beyond the second bend.</span></figcaption>
      </figure>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="ei-stat-strip" aria-label="Ear impression essentials">
    <div class="ei-wrap ei-stats">
      <article><b>Open mouth</b><span>Use a bite block from injection through curing.</span></article>
      <article><b>Deep canal</b><span>Extend beyond the second bend with a smooth tip.</span></article>
      <article><b>Full concha</b><span>Capture the helix, tragus, anti-tragus, and concha bowl.</span></article>
      <article><b>Matched pair</b><span>Send both left and right impressions, clearly labelled.</span></article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="ei-section" aria-labelledby="ei-audiologist-title">
    <div class="ei-wrap ei-intro-grid">
      <div>
        <p class="ei-kicker">Before the appointment</p>
        <h2 id="ei-audiologist-title">Start with a clean, professional impression session</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="ei-copy">
        <p>Have your impressions taken by an audiologist or a trained professional. Do not attempt a DIY impression. The clinician should inspect the ear canal first, confirm it is safe to proceed, place an otoblock correctly, and use medical-grade silicone impression material suitable for deep ear impressions.</p>
        <p>For CIEM work, the jaw position matters. Use a bite block and keep your mouth open naturally while the material is injected and while it cures. This helps account for canal movement when you sing, speak, chew, or perform on stage, reducing the chance of a seal that works only when your jaw is still.</p>
        <div class="ei-note">
          <strong>Bring this requirement to your audiologist</strong>
          <p>Please request full-shell, open-mouth impressions for custom in-ear monitors, with canal extension beyond the second bend and complete concha/helix coverage.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="ei-section dark" aria-labelledby="ei-anatomy-title">
    <div class="ei-wrap ei-anatomy-grid">
      <figure class="ei-framed-image">
        {% render 'aaw-responsive-asset-image', file: 'ear-impression-anatomy-guide.jpg', alt: 'Ear impression anatomy guide indicating the required impressioning area and concha edge thickness', width: '904', height: '890', loading: 'lazy' %}
      </figure>
      <div class="ei-copy">
        <p class="ei-kicker">Coverage map</p>
        <h2 id="ei-anatomy-title">What the impression must capture</h2>
        <p>The ear canal should be long enough to pass the second bend and preserve the natural direction of the canal. The outer ear must not be a shallow surface print; it should include the full concha bowl, helix lock, crus, tragus, anti-tragus, and the surrounding concha edge with usable thickness.</p>
        <p>That outer-ear detail gives our shell designers the landmarks needed to model a CIEM that seats consistently, distributes pressure evenly, and stays secure without over-tightening the canal.</p>
        <ul class="ei-check-list">
          <li>Canal is smooth, complete, and extended beyond the second bend.</li>
          <li>Concha bowl is filled with enough material to show its edge clearly.</li>
          <li>Helix and tragus areas are present, not thin or collapsed.</li>
          <li>No air bubbles, drag lines, torn tips, folds, or missing surfaces.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="ei-section" id="ei-quality-check" aria-labelledby="ei-quality-title">
    <div class="ei-wrap">
      <div class="ei-section-head">
        <p class="ei-kicker">Good reference</p>
        <h2 id="ei-quality-title">A quality pair from four inspection angles</h2>
        <p>A good pair should look complete from every side. The canal stalks should be long and smooth, the concha should hold enough body, and the outer-ear features should remain clear when viewed from the front, back, top, and bottom.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="ei-view-grid">
        <figure>
          {% render 'aaw-responsive-asset-image', file: 'ear-impression-good-front.jpg', alt: 'Good ear impressions viewed from the front', width: '454', height: '375', loading: 'lazy' %}
          <figcaption><b>Front</b><span>Full concha shape, visible canal direction, and clean outer-ear landmarks.</span></figcaption>
        </figure>
        <figure>
          {% render 'aaw-responsive-asset-image', file: 'ear-impression-good-back.jpg', alt: 'Good ear impressions viewed from the back', width: '450', height: '375', loading: 'lazy' %}
          <figcaption><b>Back</b><span>Enough body behind the concha so the shell can be modelled without guessing.</span></figcaption>
        </figure>
        <figure>
          {% render 'aaw-responsive-asset-image', file: 'ear-impression-good-top.jpg', alt: 'Good ear impressions viewed from the top', width: '454', height: '366', loading: 'lazy' %}
          <figcaption><b>Top</b><span>Both canals show usable depth and a stable relationship to the outer ear.</span></figcaption>
        </figure>
        <figure>
          {% render 'aaw-responsive-asset-image', file: 'ear-impression-good-bottom.jpg', alt: 'Good ear impressions viewed from the bottom', width: '450', height: '366', loading: 'lazy' %}
          <figcaption><b>Bottom</b><span>The canal tips are intact, rounded, and extended enough for CIEM shell work.</span></figcaption>
        </figure>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="ei-section dark" aria-labelledby="ei-process-title">
    <div class="ei-wrap">
      <div class="ei-section-head">
        <p class="ei-kicker">During the session</p>
        <h2 id="ei-process-title">How to get the pair right the first time</h2>
        <p>These are the practical details that most often determine whether a pair can go straight into production or needs to be retaken.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="ei-process-grid">
        <article>
          <span>01</span>
          <h3>Stabilize the jaw</h3>
          <p>Use a bite block and keep the jaw open until the material is fully cured. Do both ears with the same jaw posture so left and right behave consistently when worn.</p>
        </article>
        <article>
          <span>02</span>
          <h3>Place the otoblock deep and safely</h3>
          <p>The audiologist should position the otoblock beyond the second bend when appropriate for the ear, after inspection. Leave the otoblock attached when sending the impression.</p>
        </article>
        <article>
          <span>03</span>
          <h3>Inject slowly from deep to shallow</h3>
          <p>The material should fill the canal first, then the concha and helix area, without trapping air. A steady injection prevents bubbles, folds, and weak thin spots.</p>
        </article>
        <article>
          <span>04</span>
          <h3>Wait for a full cure</h3>
          <p>Removing the impression too early can bend the canal stalk or tear fine landmarks. After removal, the clinician should inspect both your ear and the impression.</p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="ei-section" aria-labelledby="ei-reject-title">
    <div class="ei-wrap">
      <div class="ei-section-head">
        <p class="ei-kicker">Retake warning signs</p>
        <h2 id="ei-reject-title">Common reasons impressions are not usable</h2>
        <p>If you see any of these patterns, ask for a retake before shipping. A remake at the impression stage is much faster than a refit after the CIEM is built.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="ei-warning-grid">
        <figure>
          {% render 'aaw-responsive-asset-image', file: 'ear-impression-insufficient-thin.jpg', alt: 'Insufficient ear impression example with thin outer-ear coverage', width: '355', height: '354', loading: 'lazy' %}
          <figcaption><b>Too thin</b><span>The concha and helix areas do not have enough body for reliable shell modelling.</span></figcaption>
        </figure>
        <figure>
          {% render 'aaw-responsive-asset-image', file: 'ear-impression-insufficient-short.jpg', alt: 'Insufficient ear impression example with canal not extended', width: '355', height: '354', loading: 'lazy' %}
          <figcaption><b>Not extended</b><span>The canal section is too short or incomplete, so the finished monitor may lose seal.</span></figcaption>
        </figure>
        <figure>
          {% render 'aaw-responsive-asset-image', file: 'ear-impression-insufficient-flat.jpg', alt: 'Insufficient ear impression example with flat missing outer-ear details', width: '355', height: '355', loading: 'lazy' %}
          <figcaption><b>Collapsed shape</b><span>Outer-ear landmarks are flattened or missing, leaving too little information for fit design.</span></figcaption>
        </figure>
        <figure>
          {% render 'aaw-responsive-asset-image', file: 'ear-impression-insufficient-missing-landmarks.jpg', alt: 'Insufficient ear impression example with missing landmarks', width: '355', height: '355', loading: 'lazy' %}
          <figcaption><b>Missing landmarks</b><span>Incomplete helix, tragus, or concha capture can cause unstable seating and refit risk.</span></figcaption>
        </figure>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="ei-section dark" aria-labelledby="ei-send-title">
    <div class="ei-wrap ei-send-grid">
      <div class="ei-copy">
        <p class="ei-kicker">Send to AAW</p>
        <h2 id="ei-send-title">Pack the pair so the shape survives the trip</h2>
        <p>Once both impressions pass inspection, let them fully cure, label left and right, and pack them in a crush-resistant box. Do not trim the canal, shave the concha, remove the otoblock, or force both impressions into a small container.</p>
        <p>Include your order number and contact details. If your audiologist provides a professional 3D scan, send the STL or HPS files to AAW support and keep the physical impressions until we confirm the files are accepted.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="ei-address-box">
        <h3>Shipping address</h3>
        <address>
          <strong>Advanced AcousticWerkes</strong>
          #01-03, LHK2 Building<br>
          76 Playfair Road<br>
          Singapore 367996<br>
          Attn: CIEM Department<br>
          Tel: +65 8731 5476
        </address>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="ei-final" aria-labelledby="ei-final-title">
    <div class="ei-wrap ei-final-inner">
      <h2 id="ei-final-title">The best refit is the one you never need.</h2>
      <p>Give the lab a complete, deep, clean pair of impressions and the finished CIEM starts with a better chance of sealing naturally, staying comfortable, and sounding like the model you auditioned.</p>
      <div class="ei-actions">
        <a class="ei-btn" href="{{ routes.collections_url }}/custom-iem">Browse Custom IEMs</a>
        <a class="ei-btn secondary" href="/pages/warranty-and-refit">Refit policy</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</div>

